post_text:
Yeah! Show us your first day pictures of those smiling students who had zero technical difficulties, no distractions, and had the best day ever!
*sarcasm at its finest*

Real talk - We know the first day was less than perfect for many of our families (and that's OK). There were issues with Google Meet, internet, and feelings of uncertainty. Know that we will continue to work out the kinks and navigate through this unfamiliar way of learning one day at a time.

To our parents, students and staff, YOU DID IT! You make it through the first day! Celebrate every victory and keep chugging along.
#firstdayofschool2020 #distancelearning #wpusdcares

post_text:
Last Summer Meal Distribution!
Our final summer meal distribution will be tomorrow, August 11th! The same meal pick up sites and times as previous summer pick-ups. This will provide meals through Tuesday, August 18th!

We will transition to a modified school lunch program after tomorrow (8/11)

School Year Meal Distribution
Our first meal distribution for the school year will be Thursday, August 20th which will have five breakfast and lunch meals to last through Wednesday, August, 26th. Starting August 26th, all future school meal distributions will be on Wednesdays. Sites and times are still TBD. Look for more information on this after August 15th.
Starting August 20th students will be charged based on their meal eligibility of free, reduced or paid. Please apply online as soon as possible to become eligible . All meal applications can be found using the link below.
http://www.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/index.php?sid=1506100034367501

post_text: Thank you Sierra Pacific and Lighthouse!
shared_text:
Lighthouse Counseling & Family Resource Center
August 3 at 2:04 PM ·

As a part of their commitment to the community, Sierra Pacific Industries has granted $2,500.00 to Lighthouse Counseling and Family Resource Center’s Back-to-School Backpack program to help benefit underserved children in Placer County. Community Relations Manager Mark Luster reports, “Sierra Pacific Industries is thrilled to partner with Lighthouse on this backpack project. Having the right tools to start school with is critical for our youth on multiple levels. We are honored to contribute to our community and the ongoing success of our youth.”
The Sierra Pacific Industries and Lighthouse partnership means that children in our community will have a greater chance to learn and thrive this upcoming school year.

post_text: Thank you to all of our teams who helped make this project a reality! Glen Edwards received a well-deserved face lift! 🤩
shared_text:
Rainforth Grau Architects is with Western Placer Unified School District and WPUSD - Glen Edwards Middle School.
July 29 at 11:20 AM ·

Construction is nearing completion on Glen Edwards Middle School in Placer County. The campus was completely re-imagined, including design of a contemporary two-story building featuring science, media and broadcast classrooms, a state-of-the-art gym/ music/band space, and two large campus quads.

This project totals 75,000 square feet of combined new construction and modernization, including significant site work to integrate existing buildings.

Big thanks to our collaborators and partners: the staff at GEMS, the Western Placer Unified School District and Landmark Construction!

shared_text:
Placer County
July 1 at 2:11 PM ·

211 Placer is here! 👏

ℹ️ Placer County's new information and referral system is a free, confidential, multilingual information line and website that connects people with the services and resources in their community.

📞 PHONE: Dial 2-1-1 (or 1-833-DIAL211; for TTY: 1-844-521-6697) to speak with a call specialist. Language interpretation is available.

📱 TEXT: Text your zip code to 898211. Your text plan's rates will apply.

💻 ONLINE: Visit 211Placer.org to access an online searchable database or to chat/email specialists.

Read the full announcement: https://www.placer.ca.gov/6689/211-Placer-launches-to-provide-informati

post_text: Communication update for our Scott Leaman Elementary families!
shared_text:
WPUSD - Leaman Elementary School
June 24 at 2:12 PM ·

Recently, we've received quite a few calls and emails about 'not hearing anything' after registering for the 2020-2021 school year. Rest assured, that is completely normal (even during a global pandemic believe it or not). 😉
Despite the delay in communication, we are always here to help! The district office is also working diligently over the summer to ensure every Leaman kiddo is properly accounted for until we find ourselves seated in our new home on campus.
With the help of our district office team, we are working on compiling a list of pre-registered Leaman students so we can maintain open lines of communication, even during the summer months.

What can you do in the meantime to keep up with the Joneses? 🤠
💻Take a look at our website! http://smles.wpusd.org/
👀Keep an eye on the announcement feed
👍Check up on our Facebook page
📨Send us a direct message

#LeamanLemurs #wpusd #wpusdcares

post_text: Wendy Hamasaki is an English teacher of 13 years at Glen Edwards Middle School (GEMS). Currently, she serves as the coordinator of the Honors Academy and teaches honors English classes. Hamasaki is very involved in building leaders on campus. She started the GEMS AVID program and currently serves on the Leadership Committee. She is an advocate for many of the amazing programs GEMS has to offer and is passionate about building a good foundation for students transitioning from middle school to high school. Congratulations, Wendy!

post_text:
2019-2020 Teacher of the Year (Secondary Level): Donna Tofft

Donna Tofft started teaching in this district in 1979. She taught at Glen Edwards Middle School for about five years before moving over to Lincoln High School to teach Physical Education, where she would find her home for the next thirty-five years. Beyond her teaching position, Tofft has a well-known coaching career at LHS, including over 35 years with the varsity softball program. A well-deserved honor for a committed teacher and coach. Congratulations, Donna Tofft!

post_text:
Two more weeks to mail in your bus pass for a refund!

Original post:

We understand the financial impact purchasing a bus pass for the school year can bring our families. If you purchased a semester or annual bus pass, you can mail in your bus pass for a pro-rated refund. Bus pass funds will not be rolled into next year (like cafeteria funds). Please submit by June 5, 2020.

Bus Pass Refund Process:
1. Bus Pass must be mail into:
WPUSD - BUS PASS REFUND
600 Sixth Street, Suite 400
Lincoln CA 95648
2. Payment will be confirmed in District receipt records.
3. Refund will be issued to parent on file for student.
4. Refund request must be received by last day of school – June 5, 2020

PLEASE NOTE: We MUST have the original bus pass in order to receive a refund.

Refunds for punch cards will not be available, as punch cards can be used in the next school year (no expiration date).

#WPUSD #wpusdcares

We still have about 120 meal bags to give away! Those will be passed out tomorrow at Glen Edwards Middle School from 10:30am - 12pm. In each meal bag there will be a free frozen yogurt (yumm!) 🍦

Pictured are a few awesome kiddos who brightened all of our days with a wonderful thank you sign!

With this week being our Teacher Appreciation Week, we would like to take some time to honor our teaching heroes for their continued dedication to their students, even though the classroom may look a bit different these days. That doesn't stop them from frequent video conferences with students, professional development with administration, and preparing for next year to ensure each students is on the right path for success.

Teachers, we thank you for EVERYTHING you're doing to ensure our bright students can maintain their learning. #TeacherAppreciationWeek #TeachingHeroes #DistanceLearning

post_text: While nothing could 'replace' the feeling of a traditional prom night, we hope this will help our high school kiddos.
shared_text:
LATIMES.COM
Missing prom because of coronavirus? John Krasinski's got you covered

WPUSD - LHS Fighting Zebras - Building Greatness Since 1907
April 17 at 8:00 AM ·

Good morning LHS! I wanted to put on your radar this morning the cool site, "Some Good News"- John Krasinkski is hosting a virtual prom for all of the high school students, like you guys, who missed out on having a prom this year! If you have not seen anything from this site yet, it is pretty darn cool. You should check out the experience he created for a young lady, and for the rest of us, who missed out on getting to see the play Hamilton due to COVID-19 closures. It won't be like having your own prom- but it might be worth a watch!

Here is an article with a link to his invite to his virtual prom!

https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2020-04-16/coronavirus-john-krasinski-prom-some-good-news

We welcome students back to at-home learning tomorrow after a much-needed Spring Break! We hope you were able to do something enjoyable, even if for just a few moments. We are wishing you all well and know that we are here for you. As we resume at-home learning tomorrow, here are a few reminders:
✅If you have questions regarding your student's learning, please reach out to your child's teacher and/or the principal.
✅We adjusted our district office phone hours to align with the City of Lincoln: 9am - 12pm. Please feel free to call us during that time.
✅Food distribution is tomorrow at 11am at the following locations: Glen Edwards Middle School, Lincoln High School, McBean Park, and Sheridan Elementary. 🥗🥪
✅The LAST Chromebook pick-up is Friday at Glen Edwards Middle from 10am-2pm for those who recently requested one. Please email your student's principal ASAP if you still need to request one. 💻

post_text: While our food distribution team was hard at work, our Chromebook pick-up team was simultaneously passing out over 1,000 Chromebooks!! Many principals and folks from our district office helped families get their devices so students can begin completing school work. While there is much uncertainty in these times, one thing we can truly see is the look of support on everyone's face. Everyone coming in was supportive and kind and truly wonderful. Thank you everyone who helped pass our Chromebooks. And a HUGE thank you to our tech team who made this all happen. We are all in this together and we are here for you!

post_text:
WOW! Today was AWESOME!! The district was able to pass out 12,000 meals today to students in our community. We were greeted with so many smiling faces and individuals who were very grateful for the food they received. Our food service team showed up at 5AM (yes, that's right) to start prepping the food we distributed today, and they worked tirelessly alongside many volunteers and district employees to get the job done. While we will be increasing our efforts for our next distribution (Tuesday, March 31st at 11am), we want to thank everyone who helped make today possible! It is our goal to continue learning from these experiences and make improvements. ❤️
Thank you to the great workers with the City of Lincoln, Local Government who helped with traffic and made sure things went smoothly.
#wpusdcares #12000meals #feedingstudents

For students in need of a device during school closures, Chromebooks will be available for checkout. Chromebook checkout/pick-up is Monday, March 23rd, from 8:00am to 4:00pm, at the District Technology Department (810 J Street; in the portables on the north end of the parking lot at Lincoln High School).

If your child needs a Chromebook, please request one no later than Thursday, March 19th at 4:00pm. Requests can be made by emailing your child's principal. Chromebooks will only be available for checkout on March 23rd to parents who have requested one. A parent signature will be required at the time of checkout.

post_text: A GREAT resource for kiddos during this time! Time to get moving! Thank you Sami's Circuit.
shared_text:
Sami's Circuit
March 16 at 6:36 AM ·

When I heard that schools were closing until at least April because of COVID-19, like many people, I had a moment of panic. Not only would I not get to continue my relationship with the kids in our communities, but I am self-employed. My school visits are my only source of income for my family. I went to bed that night tossing and turning, worried about my family's finances, my mortgage, keeping everyone healthy, etc. But I woke up the next morning with a sense of peace and clarity. This is NOT the time to give up!

So, STARTING THIS TUESDAY, MARCH 17TH, AT 1PM, I will be doing live broadcasts on youtube every weekday for kids who are stuck at home, don't have many ways to spend their time besides cartoons and video games, or who just want to hear from me:) I will be sharing positive messages, be available for everyone to interact with me, and of course, sharing ways to stay active and keep moving at home! Can't wait for tomorrow...You got this! https://www.youtube.com/user/TheRealSamiKader

The district will be updating information/communication sent to families on our website, specifically in the announcement feed on the main home page.

post_text:
We are excited to announce a major positive change to our kindergarten programs for the 2020-21 school year. All regular kindergarten programs will be lengthened, and we will offer extended-day kindergarten in every regular kindergarten classroom at every site. The district piloted extended-day kindergarten classes this year and found parent and student satisfaction high. This change does not affect our half-day transitional kindergarten (TK) programs.
Studies have consistently shown early intervention and support is one of the keys to a successful educational experience for students. We are dedicated to student achievement, and this program enhancement will make a difference for each student.
Approximate class time: 8:00am - 1:40pm (start time may vary slightly depending on site)

Placer County Sheriff's Office
February 3 at 8:00 AM ·

ATTENTION 📣:

Calling all talented youth artists in Placer County! Do you love to draw and think you have what it takes to design our next social media sticker?! Here’s what you need to do to qualify:

--Be 18 years of age or younger.
-Live in Placer County.
-Design a sticker incorporating “Placer County Sheriff’s Office.”

Send your drawing to SheriffPIO@placer.ca.gov ! Entries must be in .jpg or .png format. Please include a brief narrative about yourself and your age. The deadline to submit entries is February 17th. Good luck to all, and we can’t wait to see the creativity you’ll bring forward!

In order to adequately staff our schools for the 2020-2021 school year, we initiated a due date for new student and kindergarten registration. Families new to the district and anyone registering for kindergarten must have their complete registration packets in by Wednesday, February 12, 2020 by 4pm (packets may be turned in to your child’s home school). If you are registering for kindergarten and interested in participating in the Dual Language Program, you must have your registration in by the due date in order to be included in the lottery. If you have any questions regarding registration, please reach out to your child’s school site or the district office.

#kindergartenready #kindergartenregistration #newstudent #newstudentregistration

Registration Information:
http://www.wpusd.org/Parent-Resources/Registration---NEW/Next-Year-2020-2021/index.html

Dual Language Program Information:
http://www.wpusd.org/Educational-Programs/Dual-Language-Immersion-Program/index.html

shared_text:
Lincoln Public Library
January 7 at 4:02 PM ·

Did you know the Lincoln Public library has an Adult Literacy program?

Whether it is help in reading, writing, math, or even getting a GED, individuals can get one-on-one tutoring by library trained volunteers. This individualization means adults learn what they need or want to learn, at their own pace. Best of all, tutoring is free and only takes 1.5 hours of your time each week.

If you or someone you know could benefit from this, or if you might be interested in volunteering as a tutor in this program, please contact Amanda Toohey by either emailing read@lincolnca.gov or by calling the Library direction at 916-434-2410.

WPUSD - ATLAS Learning Academy
December 17, 2019 at 1:15 PM ·

Congratulations LIAM!!
Liam has graduated from high school a semester early and is headed to Sierra College. Liam took advantage of most every type of Service and Adventure opportunity available here at ATLAS. We LOVED taking him to Europe last summer as well. We will truly miss Liam...and those boots. :)
See you in June for Graduation ceremony Liam!
#atlaslearningacademy
#20192020graduate
#wpusd
